column11: Iran has not issued a foreign currency denominated bond since it issued euro-denominated bonds in 2002. After the nuclear deal speculation rose about a bond offering (The Wall Street Journal, Forbes, The Financial Tribune) and Iran has been in discussions with ratings agencies (Gulf News, The Financial Tribune). Not much progress since initial speculation has been circulated in the media. Summer slowdown of the financial markets further points against quick issuance. Recent political developments in US-Iran and Israel-Iran relationships are not conducive to foreign-denominated debt offering. On the other hand if oil price rises further there might be more interest in financing an oil-producing economy, but then again, the government debt might not be the most interesting market for global investors. There is a global appetite for yield and low-grade high-yield bonds might attract interest, but on the other hand yields on high-rated government debt have been rising lately which might reduce interest in low-rated issues. Main factor though is the short time-frame. Given how slow is the process of issuing rating, underwriting a new bond issue and securing initial sales I see it as very unlikely that anything will happen before November 1st, 2018, and definitely not before end of July.

Iran's Central bank announced intention to issue foreign denominated bonds to fund the national oil company on 7 February 2018 (article below). Oil prices are ~$60/boe. Seems likely but not certain to happen between 1 February and 30 April. Waiting for the unveiling of the plan:

While I think banks are still looking to invest in Iran, and foreign investment is a priority for Iran, the current economic instabilities will probably postpone any short term plans to start that process for at least a few months.

Upscaling the probability of the Iranian government issuing foreign currency denom bonds before 30 April: a) Steep decline in rial which has been pressurizing the government to implement policies (possible that the increasing business opportunities presented by European countries e.g. France, Austria, Italy and Asian countries e.g. India, China, South Korea may also influence the decision to stabilize the currency given the already difficult to access euro settlement system used by non-EU countries) b) Launch of the online forex platform which may push forward the pre-sales of gold coins and issuing currency bonds: https://en.trend.az/iran/business/2861830.html

The latest US congressional bill seeks to tighten oversight of the Iranian military, which may prove unacceptable to Tehran, particularly at a time of domestic tension and popular discontent. In the run-up to US mid-terms, the incentive for congress to push a bill on such a divisive issue is low. Tehran's finances are likely improving - the 2016 budget deficit was roughly 2% of GDP, and given rising oil prices in 2017 and early 2018, budgetary pressure is probably easing to some extent.
